<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Further written evidence from the Packaging and  Films Association (PAFA)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Further written evidence from the Packaging and  Films Association (PAFA)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I appeared before you and </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the environmental committee on the 18</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of December to give evidence on carrier bags in the second of three sessions and I feel compelled to follow up on some of the assertions made by the minister in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the third session which was directly after I ga</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve evidence</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Firstly the assertion that he made that the effect of exempting paper bags will be minimal. Please refer to the evidence given by the BRC which was based on the experience In the Republic of Ireland which did not mirror that. I would in addition point to the evidence in the AEA report in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that concluded that the effect of exempting paper would be to result in a net increase in waste arising </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">not a net benefit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Also and finally by exempting paper this will give a very  confusing message to the consumer  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that it is ok to use a product that has limited reuse potential and has a greater environmental impact rather than the existing product…a point that was made by NGOs including the Marine Conservation Society. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Secondly that the planned exemption for biodegradable materials would be for a material that presently does not exist! Again it is not helpful to have exemptions proposed without knowing what the purpose of such an exemption is or what impact it may have on the recycling stream or what technical and performance parameters are required. There is an equal danger if the proposal was adopted that the message may be interpreted as ‘littering is ok as the products will just biodegrade”!</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thirdly in looking at the savings in CO2 there are a number of assumptions that we would require confirmation that they have been fully factored in namely:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the increase in use of  bags for life have been factored in including their greater resource use and greater  carbon impact for each bag for life used.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That displaced secondary uses of the present so called single use bag which in fact is reused by 76% of consumers has been fully factored in including their carbon impact for each additional swing bin liner used.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We look forward to receiving the details including the carbon figures used for each product. It is worth pointing out that a recent EC document overstated the impact of plastic bags by some 84 times!</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the meantime we remain concerned that as proposed the present policy has the potential to;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To not realise any environmental benefit at all due to the exemptions proposed in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">England</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To confuse consumers by encouraging use of bags made of paper that have more resource and  environmental impacts and to use biodegradable bags which do not offer the same benefits in terms of recapturing resource as would be the case if the bags were recycled.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To continue to promulgate the message that litter associated with plastic grocery carrier bags is a significant issue when in fact it only makes up less than 1% of all litter by weight it is only found in 3.5% of all sites surveyed by KBT is a lowly 23 out of 26 items surveyed and finally is the only product  that has recorded a significant reduction in litter during the time of KBT surveys whereas other far more significant items that contribute to litter continue to grow.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finally we would like to propose for your consideration that</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That if a charge is to be recommended that the exemptions proposed be abandoned.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That if any exemptions should be proposed that they should be linked with encouraging reuse neither of the two present exemptions presently do this, they should encourage the use of products that use the least resource to do the job required again neither of the two exempted  products proposed do this, and finally that they encourage the use of products that can be recycled and use recycled content again the proposal do not does this either.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.43pt; padding-left:5.57pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That any funds raised rather than be dispersed to any charity be directed toward environmental projects and initiatives, and to communication programs run by retailers to help further educate consumers in best environmental practice.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To close on a more sombre and immediate note immediately after the EAC enquiry the direct result of the ministers assertion that he proposes to continue pursuing the biodegradable option is that the biggest film producer and recycler of film in the UK has notified me and WRAP that it plans to suspend trials to use post-consumer recycled film in building membranes due to the risks associated and the membrane failing which would result in damp penetration. This will result in a loss of a potential to recycle tens of thousands of tonnes of post-consumer film which will make plastic recycling targets in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> even more difficult to achieve, if not impossible, yet another unintended consequence of an ill thought out policy.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Barry Turner</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">6 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>